  :prose
"An AI companion in a narrative game is the deepest tool available and
the easiest one to ruin the game with. Chapter 12 taught the shape.
This appendix is the diagnostic: how to know when your companion is
working and when it isn't.

Read this before every playtest. Ask your friends specifically about
the companion. If they say 'it felt like a chatbot,' something is
wrong. If they say 'I liked her,' something is right.

---

## Signs your companion is working

**The player asks her questions.** She is not intruding; the player
is choosing to talk to her. This is the strongest signal. A working
companion is sought out.

**Her observations land.** After a reflection scene, the player
pauses for a moment before continuing. She said something that made
the player think. That is the payoff.

**Her observations vary.** Playthrough A gets a different reflection
than playthrough B, because the players did different things. The
companion is actually reading Cortex, not delivering the same line
every time.

**She has quiet moments.** The player can go 20 minutes without
seeing her. She is not a constant companion; she is an occasional
one. Her scarcity is what gives her weight.

**Players remember her.** In debriefs, players mention her by name
(or by 'the old woman on the road'). She is not just a system; she
is a character.

---

## Signs your companion is ruining the game

**The player mutes her.** The single strongest negative signal. If
your quiet-mode toggle exists (as it should) and playtests turn it
on within 15 minutes, your companion is intrusive.

**Her observations feel generic.** 'You seem to be a caring person.'
Not tied to specific things the player did. Feels like fortune-cookie
prose. This is a prompt problem — the reflection prompt didn't feed
enough context.

**She reappears at the wrong times.** Right after a big emotional
scene — the villain reveal, a death — is NOT the time for a
reflection. Let the moment breathe. Reflection scenes belong in
transitional beats.

**She uses first-person AI language.** 'As an AI, I would suggest…'
If any of her lines start like that, the illusion is dead. Prompt
against this specifically. She is a character in the world, not a
disclaimer.

**She takes too long.** `afford/deep-think` can be slow. If the
player waits more than 3 seconds for her line, she becomes a
tech-demo, not a character. Show a small 'she looks at you for a
long moment' beat while the reasoner works.

---

## The five prompts

Five prompt templates for the companion. Use them as starting
points; tune to your game's voice.

### 1. The reflection

```
The player has just done these things over the past hour:
{event_prose}

Offer a single quiet observation about what those choices might
mean about who they are becoming. Do not lecture. Do not moralize.
Do not use the word 'you' too many times. Do not begin with 'It
seems' or 'You have been.' One sentence, or two at most, in the
voice of an old woman who has met many people and has learned to
speak plainly. She is not their friend; she is not their judge; she
is the person who has been sitting on the rock.
```

### 2. The single-question consult

```
The player has done these things:
{event_prose}

They have asked: '{question}'

Answer honestly. Do not reassure and do not condemn. If the honest
answer is uncertain, say so. One or two sentences. In the voice of
someone who has known many people who asked the same question.
```

### 3. The 'previously on' recap

```
The player has been away from the story for {days_away} days. Here
are the things they did before they left:
{event_prose}

Write a two-line recap of what the story-so-far amounts to.
Not a list of facts — a sense of where the story stands and what
weight the player carries into what comes next. Second-person, but
without saying 'you' too many times.
```

### 4. The chapter summary

```
The player has just finished chapter {n}. Here is what happened in
this chapter:
{chapter_events}

Write a two-line recap in the voice of a reader looking back at
the chapter they just finished. Not a plot summary — a sense of
the emotional arc of the chapter and what it felt like.
```

### 5. The what-if consult

```
The player has asked: 'what would have happened if I had {alt-choice}
instead of {actual-choice}?'

The story does not need to reveal the actual alternate branch. Give
a poetic non-committal answer — one that respects the fact that
what happened is what happened, and honors the player's curiosity
without spoiling the design.

Two sentences at most.
```

Notice all five prompts include instructions on WHAT NOT TO DO.
Language models will otherwise slip into hedging, moralizing, over-
long responses. The prompt constrains them.

---

## Voice tuning

Tone knobs to try in your prompt:

- 'in the voice of an old woman' vs 'in the voice of a young child'
- 'plain-speaking' vs 'poetic'
- 'someone who has met many people' vs 'someone who has been alone'
- 'weight' vs 'lightness'
- 'religious phrasing' vs 'no religious phrasing'
- 'salty' vs 'gentle'

Pick voice knobs that fit your game's tone. The companion in a
warm woodland fantasy sounds different from the companion in a
gritty urban mystery.

---

## The fallback

Every companion feature must have a hand-crafted fallback for players
who cannot or will not run the AI verbs.

### Fallback for the reflection

Ten hand-written observations, each triggered by a specific Cortex
pattern.

```scheme
(define (fallback-reflection)
  (let ((helps (stat 'stat/helps))
        (kills (stat 'stat/kills))
        (mira-rep (rep 'mira)))
    (cond
      ((and (> helps 10) (= kills 0))
       \"You have not raised a hand this whole time. Some players\nnever notice they haven't.\")
      ((> mira-rep 5)
       \"You have made a friend. That is more than many manage.\")
      ((and (> kills 3) (< mira-rep 0))
       \"You have chosen to fight when you could have walked away.\nThat is a kind of person.\")
      ((and (> helps 5) (> mira-rep 0))
       \"You have been building bonds. Something is warmer.\")
      (else
       \"You are quiet, mostly. That's alright.\"))))
```

Five patterns. Not as fine-grained as a live generation, but
free and always available.

### Fallback for the summary

Just show the last three major events verbatim.

```scheme
(define (fallback-summary)
  (let ((recent (cortex/topk 3)))
    (for-each
      (lambda (event) (paint-text 20 y (event->prose event)))
      recent)))
```

No AI required. The player sees a list of three recent events. Less
poetic than a live summary, but functional.

---

## Metering care

`afford/deep-think` costs real money per use. `ai/summarize` costs
less but is not free.

### Rules for cost-conscious companion use

1. Never run `afford/deep-think` in `on-frame`. That would fire many
   times per second.
2. Every deep-think call is player-initiated. The player pressed A
   to talk to the companion. They opted in.
3. Have a `system/companion-quota` counter. If the player has used
   the deep-think reflection 5 times in this session, offer the
   fallback the sixth time. Not because it's expensive — because
   the reflection loses meaning if it happens 5+ times per session.
4. Free-tier users get fallback-only. That is a first-class
   experience, not a downgrade.

```scheme
(define (companion-reflection)
  (let ((tier (or (cortex/read 'system/user-tier) 'free))
        (session-uses (or (cortex/read 'system/companion-uses-this-session) 0)))
    (cond
      ((or (eq? tier 'free) (>= session-uses 5))
       (fallback-reflection))
      (else
       (cortex/write 'system/companion-uses-this-session (+ 1 session-uses))
       (live-reflection)))))
```

---

## The consent check

Before running any AI verb, offer the player the choice.

```scheme
(paint-text 20 40 \"'Do you want an ear?' the old woman asks.\")
(paint-text 20 100 \"[A] yes   [B] not right now\")
```

The player who says no gets no reflection. Full stop. They are not
'missing out' — they made a choice.

Some players never want an AI reflection. Their game is still
complete. Design for them; the AI is a bonus, not a requirement.

---

## Playtest questions specific to the companion

Add these to your standard playtest questions.

- Did you talk to the old woman? Why or why not?
- If yes, what did she say that stuck?
- Did she interrupt at a bad time? When?
- Did she feel like a person or like a system?
- Would you talk to her more, or less, in a next playthrough?
- Did you mute her? When?

Answers to these questions steer your companion design.

---

## Summary

Signs of a working companion. Signs of a ruining one. Five prompt
templates. Voice tuning. Fallback design. Metering care. Consent
checks. Playtest questions.

The companion is a scalpel. Handled well, she is unforgettable.
Handled badly, she is Clippy. There is no middle ground.")
